Grad-CAM from Ultrasound images

ABSTRACT4
Automated breast cancer segmentation using ultrasound images holds particular importance in the5
realm of medical imaging and healthcare. Ultrasound is a pivotal and non-invasive imaging technique6
that plays a crucial role in the early detection and diagnosis of breast cancer. The precise segmen-7
tation of breast lesions from ultrasound images is paramount, as it enables clinicians to identify and8
characterize tumors, and monitor their development over time.9
Given the variability in human interpretation, automating this process ensures consistent and objective10
results, which are vital in the realm of breast cancer diagnosis. In this project, the public available11
Breast Cancer US dataset, from Kaggle, is employed to perform automatic segmentation of the tumor12
region from the UltraSounds images, using a dilated densenet architecture.13
The segmentations are then used to classify the nature of tumor, whether benign or malignant, through14
a pretrained ResNet101 architecture, ne tuned on this dataset. Gradient-weighted Class Activation15
Mapping is used to provide explainability and validate the whole framework.16
State of the art results are obtained, using a signicantly smaller amount of parameters (190k).17
Keywords: Ultrasound Breast Cancer Computer Vision Segmentation Residual Networks18
1. OVERVIEW OF THE FRAMEWORK19
The following is a summary of the strategy of this project:20
Data Augmentation (to mitigate the unbalancing in the dataset)21
Unet implementation and training22
Unet improvement: Dilated Unet and Dilated Densnet implementation and training23
Using the ndings of MICCAI 2023s best paper to train the best model again, using the new t-loss function24
Implementing a CNN classier based on pretrained ResNet101, leveraging both the input US image and the pre-25
dicted segmentation to classify the nature of the cancer (benignant or malignant). Provide model interpretation26
through Gradient-weighted class activation mapping (Grad-CAM).27
This project was the nal submission for the Biomedical Image Processing Laboratory course at Politecnico di Milano,28
for the masters in science in Biomedical Engineering. I have reviewed this after the best paper at MICCAI 202329
highlighted a new robust loss function for image segmentation in the biomedical domain, the T-Loss, implementing it30
in my pipeline.31

3. MODEL ARCHITECTURE44
3.1. Baseline model, the UNet45
We chose to implement a u-net model, proposed by Ronneberger, Fischer and Brox, since it had been quite successful46
in biomedical segmentation tasks. U-net models are promising, as the authors were able to train their network with47
only 30 images by using aggressive image augmentation combined with pixel-wise reweighting.48
49
The u-net architecture consists of a contracting path, which collapses an image down into a set of high level features,50
followed by an expanding path which uses the feature information to construct a pixel-wise segmentation mask. The51
unique aspect of the u-net are its copy and concatenate connections which pass information from early feature maps52
to the later portions of the network tasked with constructing the segmentation mask. The authors propose that these53
3
Figure 3. Balanced dataset after the data augmentation.
connections allow the network to incorporate high level features and pixel-wise detail simultaneously. The architecture54
we used is shown in gure 4:55
Figure 4. Unet architecture, the baseline model.
3.2. Unet improvement: Dilated UNet56
Segmenting tumors requires an understanding of the broader context of how tumors are situated and their relation-57
ships with neighboring anatomical structures. It turned out that the neurons in even the deepest part of the u-net58
only had receptive elds that spanned 68x68 pixels. No part of the network could see the entire image and integrate59
global context in producing the segmentation mask. A downside of not having this global context is that, for example,60
some blobs might be misclassied as tumors, as gure 5.61
The reasoning behind this is that the model does not have enough receptive eld to understand that is very likely62
for the tumor to be in a single region of the scan and not scattered around it.63
64
Rather than adding two more downsampling layers at the cost of a huge increase in network parameters, we use65
dilated convolutions to increase the receptive elds of our network, as illustrated in gure 6.66
Dilated convolutions space out the pixels summed over in the convolution by a dilation factor. In the diagram67
above, the convolutions in the bottom layer are regular 33 convolutions. The next layer up, we have dilated the68
convolutions by a factor of 2, so their eective receptive eld in the original image is 77. The top layer convolutions69
are dilated by 4, producing 1515 receptive elds. Dilated convolutions produce exponentially expanding receptive70
elds with depth, in contrast to linear expansion for stacked conventional convolutions.71
72
Figure 7 shows how increasing the eld of view of the networks overcomes the error in segmentation phase.73
4
Figure 5. Misclassication of healthy region as tumor by the baseline model.
Figure 6. Dilated UNet exponentially increases the eld of view of the neurons in the UNet.
3.3. Improvement of the dilated UNet, dilated densenet74
For segmentation tasks, we need both global context and information from multiple scales to produce the pixel-wise75
mask. What if we only used dilated convolutions to generate global context, rather than downsampling to smash76
the image down to a small height and width? Now that the convolutional layers all have the same size, we could use77
copy and concatenate connections between all the layers. This new architecture takes the name of dilated densenet,78
and its architecture is illustrated in gure 8.79
80
In densenets, the output of the rst convolutional layer is fed as input into all subsequent layers, and similarly with81
the second, third, and so forth. The authors show that densenets have several advantages:82
they alleviate the vanishing-gradient problem, strengthen feature propagation, encourage feature reuse, and sub-83
stantially reduce the number of parameters.84
85
At publication, densenets had surpassed the state of the art on the CIFAR and ImageNet classication benchmarks.86
However, densenets have a serious drawback: they are extremely memory intensive since the number of feature maps87
grow quadratically with network depth. The authors used transition layers to cut down on the number of feature88
maps midway through the network in order to train their 40, 100 and 250 layer densenets. Dilated convolutions89
5
Figure 7. Misclassication is solved using dilated unet.
Figure 8. Dilated densenet architecture.
eliminates the need for such deep networks and transition layers since only 8 layers are needed to see an entire90
256256 image.91
92
In the nal convolutional layer of a dilated densenet, the neurons have access to global context as well as features93
produced at every prior scale in the network. In our work, we use an 8-layer dilated densenet and vary the growth94
rate from 12 to 32. Heres the astounding aspect: the dilated densenet is extremely parameter ecient. Our nal95
model uses only 190K parameters, a point well come back to when discussing results. Lets look at how to train these96
models, and then move on to their performance in segmenting right ventricles.97

5. RESULTS124
Table 1 gives an overview of the obtained results. The u-net baseline achieves a dice score of 0.87 (0.06) on the125
training set, which means the model has little bias and the capacity to perform at human-level (reported to be around126
0.9). However, the validation accuracy is 0.79 (0.23), indicating a large variance.127
This led to an examination of edge cases, an understanding of receptive elds, and ultimately the dilated u-net128
architecture. It beats the original u-net and achieves 0.92 (0.08) on the training set and 0.83 (0.19) on the validation129
set.130
Finally, dilated densenets were loosely inspired by the similarity between dilated convolutions and tensor networks131
used in physics. This architecture achieves 0.91 (0.10) on the training set and 0.82 (0.15) on the validation set with132
only 0.19M parameters.133
All of these results are obtained employing the classic dice weighted pixelwise cross entropy. On the other hand, in134
October 2023 a new loss function has been proposed at the best paper at the MICCAI 2023 conference, known as135
t-Loss. I decided to train the dilated dense net using this new loss function, and the results improve. The dice on136
training increases to 0.94, with and std equal to 0.14, and it gets 0.87 (0.19) on the testset, proving how this new137
framework is more robust and informative for the model to learn.138

6. CNN FOR TUMOR CLASSIFICATION AND EXPLAINATION148
Two dierent ML based approaches are used to classify the images as Healthy (normal), Benign or Malignant.149
A CNN architecture has been employed, known as ResNet101. The model weights, pretrained on the ImageNet-1k150
dataset, are used as starting point, and transfer learning is employed to ne tune the model parameter to perform151
well on this specic dataset.152
153
For the rst approach, only the segmentation mask is used to classify the images. In the second approach, the154
masking is overlayed to the original image, which leads to a signicant improvement in the results, as can be seen in155
gure 11. For the seek of interpretability of the model, a Gradient-weighted class activation mapping (Grad-CAM)156
visualization is provided. Grad-CAM is an interpretable technique that highlights the most important regions in an157
image used by a convolutional neural network (CNN) for making a classication decision, aiding in understanding why158
a specic classication was made. In breast tumor classication, Grad-CAM can help identify which features or areas159
in a mammogram image are inuential in the models decision, assisting radiologists in validating and interpreting the160
models predictions for malignancy or benignity:161
The computed Grad-CAM results from the nal convolutional layer are presented in gure 12. In these images,162
Grad-CAM eectively identies the hyperechoic regions and the indistinct edges associated with malignant tumors. In163
contrast, Grad-CAM maps for benign cases exhibit a more uniform distribution, indicating the absence of cancerous164
growth and greater tissue homogeneity. This dierence between the two classes is demonstrating that the convolutional165
layers in our model extract relevant features for the classier, and makes us conclude that the proposed classiers166
overall performance is satisfactory and holds promise for clinical applications.167
